biography: Milk is built to enable creative expression and collaboration.

latestIgtvVideos.caption: This afternoon we’ll be releasing a special guest curation takeover by @sav_britt , founder and CEO of @thebrittprint . She will be taking over @milk to share some of the most inspiring and up and coming Black creators and creative entrepreneurs she has an eye on! Savannah is a public relations thought leader, and has helped shape the identity of some of the biggest talent and brands across the fashion and music spaces. The agency Savannah founded has cultivated relevant work with clients such as Burna Boy, Gucci Mane, Lil Yachty, and Smoke DZA, along with providing a bridge between various African stars and the US. Stay tuned :)

Rest in peace to Mick Rock (@therealmickrock), an icon in the world of music photography and a dear friend of our community. His work in the 1970’s with the likes of David Bowie, Lou Reed, and the Sex Pistols amongst a number of others made him as integrated to the world of rock and roll as the musicians he shot. 

Milk Gallery has had several exhibits with Mick over the years. The two most recent exhibits were “Rebel Rebel” in 2008 in collaboration with Russell Young (@bankrobbercalifornia) and the charity Art of Elysium, as well as “Mick Rock: David Bowie” in 2016, an intimate look at his unparalleled access and breadth of work involving Bowie. This video was produced by the Milk team and the multi-disciplinary creative @paulbui as a short documentary capturing Mick’s career and life in conjunction with our work with him.

You will be missed, Mick 🙏 

---

latestIgtvVideos.title: Milk Presents - In the Studio with Weslah
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
Hailing from the Southern-Baptist churches of Tennessee, Wesley Berryman is the designer and artist that's rising to the top of NYC's fashion world. Inspired by @alexandermcqueen, Berryman’s designs and online alias, @weslah, have an unapologetic and provocatively futuristic aesthetic that cannot be limited to words. ⁣
⁣
Over the years, he's collaborated on pieces for several artists such as @kimpetras and @rosalia.vt, alongside a fashion week show for his collection Obsession in the Fall of 2019. Whether it’s a dress for @ladygaga’s tour performance or a custom garment for @beyonce, this designer kicks off his ideas with sketches, fabrics, decadent rhinestones, and religious iconography pinned across his studio walls.⁣
⁣
Before, NY's shelter-in-place order, Milk visited Berryman's studio. This week, we caught up with over the interweb to hear about his updated plans for 2020, what projects he is currently working on, and the home to all of his creations: his studio.⁣
⁣
CREDITS:⁣
DIRECTOR + CINEMATOGRAPHER: @kamkorderz ⁣
PRODUCERS: @ellajayes + @merilyn___ ⁣
MUSIC: @bbbskyyy ⁣
PHOTOS + INTERVIEW: @harshhy

latestIgtvVideos.title: Milk Presents - In the Studio with ØBLANC
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
Three months after graduating @parsonsschoolofdesign, @oliviaoblanc found herself with her own namesake brand, ØBLANC, and an upcoming collaboration with @adidas. The young designer, hailing from New Orleans, now calls New York her home and attributes it to one of her biggest inspirations for the work-wear influenced label. For those unfamiliar with Oblanc’s work, one scroll through @kendalljenner’s IG should familiarize you with this rising designer’s vision. Despite being less than three years old, ØBLANC has made waves in the NYC and global fashion scene.

At the top of 2020,  we visited Oblanc’s studio to chat with her about getting her foot in the door of the fashion world, her past internships with @hoodbyair, and her knack for sewing. 
CREDITS: 
PHOTOGRAPHER: @k.m
DIRECTOR + CINEMATOGRAPHER + EDITOR: @kamkorderz 
PRODUCERS: @ellajayes + @merilyn___
MUSIC: @bbbskyyy 
Additional Footage Courtesy of @oliviaoblanc.

latestIgtvVideos.title: Milk Presents - In the Studio with Carla Maldonado
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
In honor of Earth Day, we’re featuring @carlamaldonado, a multimedia artist who extensively covers climate activism through the eyes of the rebels, misfits, and revolutionaries. Before the self-quarantines in New York began, we met with the Brazilian artist @somad.studio.

Upon entering, we were met with glaring red lights and layered footage, reflections of the symbolism that is consistent through all her pieces. Her work highlights the need for restoration and protection projects for Indigenous lands in Brazil while featuring the environmental activists in the face of this crisis.

Living between Trump’s America and Bolsonaro’s Brazil, Maldonado works to expose the reality of both countries. In her studio, we talked to the artist about collaboration, censorship, and how ecofeminism is key to changing our world’s current power dynamics. 
CREDITS: 
Interview by @jurutz
DIRECTOR + EDITOR + CINEMATOGRAPHER: @liviadilucia
PHOTOGRAPHER: @serichai
PRODUCERS: @ellajayes + @merilyn___

latestIgtvVideos.title: Milk Presents - Love Series <3: Elle + Trenton
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
Love has the power to transform anything; especially creativity.  Milk will sit down with people who have seen their art flourish with the help of a loved one (be it romantic, platonic, or familial.) Prior to social distancing regulations, we spoke to the NY-based couple, @ellebaness and @trentonparrott. Now, more than ever, we ask all of our Milk fam to reach into their communities to find the love and support we all need during these trying times. How are you staying connected and creative in our world right now?

latestPosts.caption:
New York, New York by @amirbangs 

“These clips are inspired by my favorite cinematographers and directors. I would like to think of each clip like it’s the beginning or ending of a movie, or the transition between scenes. Not necessarily have a protagonist, but the color, light, movement, or weather should evoke a sense of cinema.” - @amirbangs

“SETTLE DOWN” by @inter_disciplinary and Zachary Swearingen (in memoriam)

Shot in 2018, the series plays with color, pattern, and composition to explore narratives around feminine expectations — with Zachary behind the lends and Haley as the figure in frame.

“We were both very proud of this work and where it was going.” - @inter_disciplinary 

Zachary passed away unexpectedly in 2020, leaving SETTLE DOWN as a powerful memory of their shared vision.

latestPosts.caption:
Artist Spotlight: Mlingani II by @muholizanele 

This week’s artist spotlight features Zanele Muholi, a South African visual activist and renowned photographer whose work honors Black queer and trans lives, the urgency of visibility, and why self-validation is revolutionary.

“When you use a safety pin, it’s meant to bind whatever two pieces together, and it needs to be done with care.

So when we put each other’s hands together, regardless of how we speak as gendered humans and how we speak as people with feelings, we should make sure that we do that with safety. The person needs to feel safe and know that more than an ally, this is my sister, this is my friend, regardless of your tribe, regardless of your race, regardless of your backgrounds.” - @muholizanele 

Credits:
Image courtesy of @caseykelbaugh @southernguildgallery

Artist Spotlight: Exiles by @sunilgupta7402

This week’s artist spotlight features Sunil Gupta, whose work Exiles reframes what it means to exist as a queer man in the face of displacement and fear— bringing the unseen into view.

“I think a lot of the problems we have with each other stem from not knowing other people—what they look like, what they act like, who they are… I wanted to give it a face.”– @sunilgupta7402

Our lens on contemporary art’s shifting landscape, captured during @Friezeofficial at The Shed. 

Moving through breathtaking installations and boundary-pushing works from 65+ galleries, we found ourselves equally drawn to the unexpected:

The backstage gallery “employee rooms” where bananas, lunch boxes, and Frieze water bottles created accidental still lifes beside six-figure masterworks. The art world’s most honest compositions revealed themselves in these unguarded spaces.

Artist Spotlight Cate Blanchett by @szilvesztermako

Szilveszter Makó — Hungarian-born, Milano-based photographer & art director. His work is shaped by brutalist precision, chiaroscuro light, and the raw poetry of texture. Handmade props, surreal tones, deep grain — every frame feels touched by hand. A visual language of the grotesque, the forgotten, and the obsessively constructed.

Watch Brooklyn-based innovator Mecca McDonald @meccaanism as she partners with @Coach’s solution to fashion’s waste problem @coachtopia for a biocharm DIY event where guests created their own eco-friendly bag charms. Her strategy? She turns potatoes into plastic materials! 

A @776foundation recipient founded by @alexisohanian which supports Gen Z climate visionaries, Mecca continues to push boundaries in the sustainable materials space one potato at a time.
